'''Marwar Junction railway station''' is located in [[Pali district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of  [[Rajasthan]] .  It serves the census town  at [[Marwar Junction]].

==The railway station==
Marwar Junction railway station is at an elevation of {{convert|267|m|ft}} and was assigned the code â€“ MJ.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/marwar-junction-mj/129 |title= Arrivals at Marwar Junction|publisher= indiarailinfo| accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

==History==
Rajputana State Railway extended the Delhi-Ajmer {{RailGauge|1000mm}} wide [[metre gauge]] line to Ahmeabad in 1881.<ref name=irfcaii>{{cite web|url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history2.html |title= IR History: Early Days II (1870-1899)| publisher=IRFCA| accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> It was converted to {{RailGauge|1676mm}} wide [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history5.html |title= IR History: Part V (1970-1995)| publisher=IRFCA| accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

The Rajputana-Malwa Railway built the metre gauge line from Marwar Junction to [[Pali]] in 1882. Later, this section was extended to [[Jodhpur]] and formed the Jodhpur Railway.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.wiki.fibis.org/index.php?title=Jodhpur-Bikaner_Railway|title = Jodhpur-Bikaner Railway| publisher= fibis| accessdate = 30 April 2014}}</ref> The line now runs up to [[Munabao]] on the India-Pakistan border and has been fully converted to broad gauge.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-inter.html  |title = Geography:International| publisher=IRFCA | accessdate = 30 April 2014}}</ref>

The [[Mavli]]-Marwar metre gauge line was opened in 1936.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history3.html  |title = IR History: Part III (1900-1947)| publisher=IRFCA | accessdate = 30 April 2014}}</ref>

== Cultural references ==

=== In fiction ===
The station is mentioned in Chapter&nbsp;1 of [[Rudyard Kipling|Rudyard Kipling's]] short story [[The Man Who Would Be King]] which was first published in ''[[The Phantom Rickshaw and other Eerie Tales]]'' (1888).  It is the meeting place of the narrator, Kipling in all but name, and [[Daniel Dravot]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/phantomrickshawo00kiplrich#page/66/mode/2up/search/marwar|title=The Phantom Rickshaw and other Eerie Tales|last=Kipling|first=Rudyard|publisher=Samson Low, Marston, Searle & Rivington Ltd|year=1888|isbn=|location=|pages=67}}</ref>

